Reference: [https://angular.io/api/common/NgSwitch][1]


  [1]: https://angular.io/api/common/NgSwitch

You can use [NgSwitch Directive][1] for this

	&lt;container-element [ngSwitch]=&quot;switch_expression&quot;&gt;
	  &lt;!-- the same view can be shown in more than one case --&gt;
	  &lt;some-element *ngSwitchCase=&quot;match_expression_1&quot;&gt;...&lt;/some-element&gt;
	  &lt;some-element *ngSwitchCase=&quot;match_expression_2&quot;&gt;...&lt;/some-element&gt;
	  &lt;some-other-element *ngSwitchCase=&quot;match_expression_3&quot;&gt;...&lt;/some-other-element&gt;
	  &lt;!--default case when there are no matches --&gt;
	  &lt;some-element *ngSwitchDefault&gt;...&lt;/some-element&gt;
	&lt;/container-element&gt;

Alternatively, you can also use [NgIf Directive][2], but the NgSwitch is more suitable for single expression for multiple choices.

    &lt;div *ngIf=&quot;condition&quot;&gt;Content to render when condition is true.&lt;/div&gt;


  [1]: https://angular.io/api/common/NgSwitch
  [2]: https://angular.io/api/common/NgIf

