answers.body_markdown:
Your Typescript imports typically should not end in extensions. Instead, Webpack should be configured to append the extensions as needed.

As in the [Microsoft Typescript Vue SFC example on GitHub](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript-Vue-Starter/blob/master/webpack.config.js#L46), your &quot;resolve.extensions&quot; list should include `.ts`:

```json
  resolve: {
    extensions: [&#39;.ts&#39;, &#39;.js&#39;, &#39;.vue&#39;, &#39;.json&#39;],
    alias: {
      &#39;vue$&#39;: &#39;vue/dist/vue.esm.js&#39;
    }
  },
```

As in the `resolve.extensions` documentation:

&gt; Attempt to resolve these extensions in order.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; _If multiple files share the same name but have different extensions, webpack will resolve the one with the extension listed first in the array and skip the rest._

